  "summary": "## Security Analysis Summary: requests-2.19.0\n\n### Critical Vulnerability Identified: CWE-522 - Insufficiently Protected Credentials\n\n**Vulnerability: Authorization Header Leak During HTTPS\u2192HTTP Redirects**\n\n#### Description\nThe `rebuild_auth` function in `requests/sessions.py` (line 231-253) contains a critical security flaw where it only validates hostname changes when deciding whether to strip Authorization headers during redirects, but **does not check for protocol/scheme downgrades** from HTTPS to HTTP.\n\n#### Technical Details\n- **Location**: `requests/sessions.py`, function `rebuild_auth` (lines 231-253)\n- **Issue**: The function deletes the Authorization header at line 246, but the guarding condition at line 245 only compares hostnames (`original_parsed.hostname != redirect_parsed.hostname`)\n- **Missing Check**: No validation exists for scheme changes (e.g., `https://` \u2192 `http://`)\n- **Impact**: When a redirect occurs from HTTPS to HTTP with the same hostname, the Authorization header containing credentials is preserved and sent over an unencrypted HTTP connection\n\n#### Evidence from Analysis\n1. Found `rebuild_auth` function that handles authorization during redirects\n2. Identified Delete operation for Authorization header at line 246\n3. Confirmed the guarding condition at line 245 only checks hostname equality\n4. **Verified NO scheme/protocol comparison exists in the function** - no references to `.scheme` attribute found\n\n#### Security Impact\n- **Severity**: HIGH/CRITICAL\n- **CWE**: CWE-522 (Insufficiently Protected Credentials)\n- **Attack Scenario**: An attacker controlling a redirect endpoint could downgrade from HTTPS to HTTP while maintaining the same hostname, causing credentials (Basic Auth, Bearer tokens, etc.) to be transmitted in cleartext over the network\n- **Affected Versions**: requests-2.19.0 (and likely earlier versions)\n\n#### Recommendation\nThe `rebuild_auth` function should also check for scheme downgrades and strip Authorization headers when redirecting from HTTPS to HTTP, regardless of hostname matching.\n\n### Analysis Coverage\n- Examined 19 Python files totaling 3,621 lines of code\n- Focused on redirect and authentication handling functions\n- Executed 12 CodeQL queries targeting credential protection during redirects\n- Identified key functions: `rebuild_auth`, `resolve_redirects`, `handle_redirect`\n",
